Today I studied PCA in depth — how it finds directions of maximum variance,
projects data onto new axes called principal components, and reduces
dimensionality by keeping only the top N components while discarding noise.

Also worked through when PCA is needed — curse of dimensionality,
correlated/redundant features — and the key distinction between:
- PCA before clustering (preprocessing)
- PCA after clustering (visualization only)

Started with the Credit Card dataset (CC GENERAL.csv, 17 features) for the
PCA-first strategy. Problem: PCA produced 8 components before hitting 85%
variance, so clustering happened in 8D and the scatter plot was still
an approximation showing only PC1 and PC2.

Switched to Country Socioeconomic dataset (Country-data.csv, 9 features)
where GDP, income, health spending, child mortality and life expectancy are
strongly correlated. PCA compressed these down to 2-3 components capturing
75-85%+ variance, meaning clustering happened directly in 2D/3D PCA space
and the scatter plot is a perfectly accurate picture of the clustering —
no gap between clustering space and visualization space.

Extended the scatter plot to 3D using projection='3d' and ax.scatter with
three PC coordinate arrays. The 3D plot is interactive and rotatable in
VS Code/Jupyter for better cluster inspection.

Datasets:
- Credit Card: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arjunbhasin2013/ccdata
- Country Socioeconomic: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rohan0301/unsupervised-learning-on-country-data
